# UNIUN – Application Specification (MVP)

## Overview

UNIUN is an **offline-first decentralized social application** built on Nostr.

The app is centered around **Notes**, which act as:

* posts (like Twitter)
* messages (like chat)
* knowledge units (graph-based)

All data is stored locally and synced via Nostr relays.

No backend server is used. The app itself handles all logic.

---

## Core Concepts

### Notes

Notes are the fundamental unit.

A note can contain:

* text
* image (URL)
* user mentions
* references to other notes

Notes are stored locally and published to relays.

---

### Graph-Based References

Notes can reference other notes using tags.

This creates a **graph structure** instead of a simple thread.

A note can:

* reply to one note
* reference multiple notes

This is used for:

* threads
* idea linking
* knowledge graph

---

### Vishnu (Feed + Notes)

Vishnu is the main feed and note system.

Features:

* view all notes (feed)
* filter by channel
* see note threads
* like notes
* save notes locally

Notes appear in a clean feed UI.

---

### Brahma (Create Note)

Brahma is used to create notes.

User can:

* write text
* add image
* tag users
* reference existing notes
* choose channel

Also includes:

* preview of note reference graph before posting

---

### Shiv (AI Assistant)

Shiv is a fully on-device AI assistant. No cloud API. No data leaves the phone.

**Model selection:**
User picks from supported models (Qwen3 0.6B, DeepSeek R1, Gemma 4 E2B, Gemma 4 E4B) via `AIModelSelectionPage`. Selection is persisted in `AppSettingsModel` (Isar). If no model is active, Shiv redirects to the selection screen.

**What Shiv can do:**
* Answer questions using your own saved notes as context (RAG)
* Summarize topics across your notes
* Reason over your personal knowledge base
* Maintain multi-turn conversation history per session

**RAG pipeline:**
1. On tab open — embedding model (all-MiniLM-L6-v2, TFLite, ~80MB) is loaded. User profile + own notes build a personalized system instruction.
2. On each message — the question is embedded, compared against saved-note vectors (cosine similarity), top-K matches are injected as context before the model sees the question.
3. `InferenceChat` (flutter_gemma 0.13.x) manages conversation history internally — each turn only receives the current question + RAG context, not the full history.

**Conversation management:**
* Each chat is a `ShivConversation` (persisted in Isar forever).
* Messages form a linked list via `parentId` — future branch-tree view is possible without schema changes.
* Auto-title: the first 40 characters of the first user message become the conversation title.
* History drawer slides in from the left (Scaffold drawer). Swipe a conversation to delete.

**Stack:** flutter_gemma 0.13.1 · tflite_flutter · all-MiniLM-L6-v2 · Isar

---

### Channels (Public Only)

Channels are used for grouping discussions.

Examples:

* #general
* #ai
* #design

Features:

* anyone can read
* anyone can post (MVP)

Channels are implemented using NIP-28 (Kind 40 = create, Kind 42 = message).

No private channels in MVP.

---

### Direct Messages (DM)

Simple 1:1 messaging using Kind 14 (NIP-17).

MVP:

* uses Kind 14 message events
* basic 1:1 only

Future:

* full 3-layer encryption (Kind 14 → Kind 13 seal → Kind 1059 gift wrap)

---

### Saved Notes

* stored locally only (Isar)
* not synced to relay
* used for personal bookmarking and RAG (AI)

---

### No Delete

Notes are permanent. There is no delete — not local, not relay.

This is intentional: **feed freedom**. Once a note is published to the Nostr network, it exists. The app does not pretend otherwise.

NIP-09 is not used.

---

## Architecture

Offline-first design:

```
Flutter UI
→ Isar DB (local source of truth)
← EmbeddedServer (SyncEngine + RelayConnector + EventQueue)
↔ Relay network (WebSocket)
```

Relay is used only for:

* publishing events
* receiving events

All logic is handled inside the app. No backend server.

---

## Nostr Protocol Usage

NIP set for MVP:

* NIP-01 → base event system (all events)
* NIP-10 → note references and threading (e-tag markers)
* NIP-28 → public channels (Kind 40/41/42)
* NIP-17 → direct messages (Kind 14)
* NIP-44 → encryption (future, for full DM wrapping)

Not used:

* NIP-09 → deletion — intentionally excluded (feed freedom)

---

## Event Structure

All data is stored as Nostr events.

| Kind | Meaning |
|------|---------|
| 0    | User profile |
| 1    | Public note (feed) |
| 7    | Reaction (like) |
| 14   | Direct message |
| 40   | Channel creation |
| 41   | Channel metadata update |
| 42   | Channel message |

Tags used in Kind 1:

* `e` → referenced note (graph edge)
* `p` → user mention
* `t` → topic/channel tag

---

## Data Handling

* all notes stored locally in Isar
* synced with relay via EmbeddedServer
* Isar is the source of truth — UI never reads from relay directly

---

## Scope (MVP)

Included:

* notes feed (Vishnu)
* create note with references (Brahma)
* knowledge graph view
* public channels (NIP-28)
* direct messages (Kind 14)
* local AI assistant with RAG (Shiv)
* saved notes + embeddings

Not included:

* private groups
* channel permissions
* delete / NIP-09
* advanced moderation

---

## Goal

UNIUN provides a **decentralized, offline-first social + knowledge system** combining:

* social feed
* chat
* knowledge graph
* local AI

All controlled by the user, without central servers.
